{
  "query": "What evidence exists for creating or managing land to provide nesting sites for ground-nesting bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence exists for creating and managing nesting sites for ground-nesting bees. One replicated controlled trial in Germany and four small trials showed that artificially exposed areas of bare soil can be successfully colonised by ground-nesting solitary bees and wasps within the first or second year (Action ID 13). Additionally, extensive research on artificial nest sites shows that many species of solitary bee, including ground-nesting species, will readily occupy artificial nesting structures. Studies across Europe, North and South America, and Asia involving 30 replicated trials demonstrated that 29 trials showed occupancy by solitary bees in artificial nest boxes, though these were primarily cavity-nesting rather than strictly ground-nesting species. One trial specifically tested soil-filled nest boxes for the mining bee Andrena flavipes in the UK, but they were not occupied, suggesting that simply providing soil-filled containers may not be effective for ground-nesting species (Action ID 47).",
  "action_ids": [
    "13",
    "47"
  ]
}

