{"query": "On UK farmland, how does sowing field margins with agricultural forage plants compare to native wildflower mixes for attracting bumblebees?", "summary": "On UK farmland, both agricultural forage plants and native wildflower mixes in field margins attract bumblebees, with different advantages. Agricultural nectar and pollen mixes containing perennial leguminous flowering plants attract significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy or cropped field margins (action 18). Three replicated trials showed that agricultural forage plant mixes, particularly those containing legumes, can attract greater numbers of bumblebees than perennial wildflower mixes, especially in the first year after sowing. However, these agricultural legume margins degrade in their value to bumblebees over time and require re-sowing every few years to maintain effectiveness.

Native wildflower seed mixes also effectively support bumblebees on UK farmland. Five replicated trials showed that uncropped field margins sown with wild flowers support higher abundance of foraging bumblebees than cropped field edges, grassy margins or naturally regenerated uncropped margins (action 19). The perennial leguminous herbs in wildflower seed mixtures are particularly important forage sources for bumblebees, especially for long-tongued species. One trial demonstrated that common long-tongued bumblebee species (Bombus pascuorum and B. hortorum) strongly preferred plots of perennial wildflower seed mix over annual forage plant mixes.

Both approaches are more effective than conventional field margins, cropped areas, or naturally regenerated margins for supporting bumblebee populations. The choice between agricultural forage mixes and native wildflowers may depend on specific management goals, with agricultural mixes potentially offering greater initial attraction but requiring more frequent maintenance, while native wildflower mixes may provide more sustained benefits particularly for specialized bumblebee species.", "action_ids": ["18", "19"]}

