{
  "query": "What factors are known to influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites provided for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from multiple replicated trials, several key factors influence artificial nest site occupancy and productivity for solitary bees. Nest box design is crucial - reed stem and wooden grooved-board designs produce more bees per nest than plastic-lined holes or plastic/paper tubes, which are less productive due to parasitism and mould issues (action ID 47). The nesting material also matters, with reed stems or wood showing the highest production of red mason bees compared to other materials (action ID 80). Proximity to foraging resources is essential, with research indicating nest boxes must be within 150-600 m of foraging areas, as several European species have foraging ranges limited to this distance (actions 47, 80). The duration of provision also impacts success, with studies showing occupied solitary bee nests can double over three years with repeated nest box provision at sites (actions 47, 80). However, parasitism and predation significantly affect productivity, with mortality rates ranging from 2% to 56% across different studies, though some sites showed only 13% overall mortality with 2% successfully parasitized (action 47). Competition from introduced species can reduce occupancy by native bees, as European earwigs and introduced European leafcutter bee species sometimes occupy boxes more frequently than native bees (action 47). Additionally, ant exclusion can improve offspring production, demonstrated in a study of the Australian bee Exonuera nigrescens (action 46). Occupancy rates vary considerably, with studies reporting 1-26% of available cavities occupied (action 80).",
