{
  "query": "What factors, such as diet and social parasitism, have been shown to affect the success of captive-rearing and reintroducing bumblebee colonies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several factors affect the success of captive-rearing and reintroducing bumblebee colonies. Diet composition significantly influences reproductive success - colonies fed on freshly frozen pollen produced larger queens that survived better and produced larger colonies than those fed on dried, frozen pollen (Action ID 50). Two replicated trials showed that B. terrestris workers can produce more offspring when fed pollen with higher protein content (Action ID 50). Social parasitism by cuckoo bees (Bombus [Psithyrus] spp.) is another critical factor, with studies showing highly variable parasitism rates from 25-79% in released colonies (Action ID 52). One UK trial demonstrated that social parasitism could be reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate rather than very high nectar and pollen availability, and by releasing them later rather than earlier in the season (Action ID 52). Supplementary feeding showed mixed results - one Canadian trial found it improved reproductive success of captive-reared colonies but did not reduce parasite load, while a US trial found no increase in colony productivity from supplementary feeding (Action ID 52). Captive rearing methods also mattered, with one trial finding that queens gradually decreased in weight over four years of artificial rearing (Action ID 50), and laboratory rearing showed variable success for different North American bumblebee species, with some species like B. fervidus laying eggs but experiencing larval mortality before reaching adulthood (Action ID 50).",
  "action_ids": [
    "52",
